'''Kokuwakura Shrine''' (こくわくらじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in Agedo, {{jalink|Taira (Iwaki City)|Q128846894|Taira}}, {{jalink|Iwaki City|Q274384}}, {{jalink|Fukushima Prefecture|Q71707}}. It is a {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|Shikinaisha (minor shrine)}}, and under the {{jalink|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|former shrine ranking system}} it was designated a prefectural shrine.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it was founded in the first year of {{jalink|Daido (Japan)|Q1373191|Daidō}} ({{jalink|806|Q30021}}). It is an {{jalink|Engishiki-listed shrine}} and one of the seven Shikinaisha of Iwaki Province. In ancient times it was said to be the general guardian shrine of the four districts of Iwaki ({{jalink|Kikuta District|Q11619613}}, {{jalink|Iwaki District|Q11587876}}, {{jalink|Iwamae District|Q11587858}}, and {{jalink|Naraha District|Q11541347}}).

As one of the “Three Shrines of Taira Castle,” deities protecting {{jalink|Taira Castle}}, it was venerated by successive lords of the castle.

In {{jalink|Keichō|Q1328185}} 6 ({{jalink|1602|Q6727}}), construction of {{jalink|Iwaki-Taira Castle|Q11587869}} reduced the shrine’s land, leading to its decline. However, in {{jalink|Bunsei|Q1327119}} 9 ({{jalink|1826|Q7004}}), the fourth lord of the {{jalink|Taira Domain}}, {{jalink|Naitō Yoshitsuna|Q8514975}}, restored a small {{jalink|Inari}} shrine that had stood in Sakuramachi and relocated it to the present site.

In March of {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}} 6 ({{jalink|1873|Q7757}}), it was elevated to the rank of {{jalink|Prefectural Shrine}}. Even after the abolition of the {{jalink|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534}} in {{jalink|Shōwa|Q327567}} 21, it continued to be affectionately called “Kensha” (prefectural shrine).

In {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}} 7, the {{jalink|cliff|Q1174791}} on the southern front was cut away to create the “Men’s Slope,” and in {{jalink|Taishō|Q329174}} 10 the “Women’s Slope” was completed.

=== Shrine Name ===
“{{jalink|Ko|Q1307938}}” is said to mean “{{jalink|silkworm}},” symbolizing “clothing”; the agricultural tool “{{jalink|hoe|Q131154}}” represents “food”; and “{{jalink|kura (storehouse)}}” represents “shelter.” Together, the name is said to express the divine virtues of the enshrined deity governing “{{jalink|clothing, food, and shelter}}.”

=== Shrine Buildings ===
In April of {{jalink|Tenpō|Q1369045}} 2, a fire destroyed the {{jalink|shrine buildings}}, and most {{jalink|ancient documents|Q89298567}} and {{jalink|sacred treasures|Q11589458}} were lost.

In May of {{jalink|Kaei|Q1146125}} 6, the current main hall was constructed by master carpenter Yokota Mokusaemon of {{jalink|Takine Town|Q7678319}}.

Under the design and supervision of Tsukamoto Yoshitaka, a consultant to the {{jalink|Ministry of Education (Japan)|Q11080185}}, the present {{jalink|Heiden|Q3076699}} and {{jalink|Haiden|Q3125745}} were completed in {{jalink|Shōwa|Q327567}} 4.

