[[File:Kokuwakura Jinja Iriguchi.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Shrine grounds entrance}}]]
'''Kokuwakura Shrine''' (こくわくらじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Agedo, {{ill|lt=Taira (Iwaki City)|Q128846894|qid=Q128846894|lt=Taira|1=Taira}}, {{ill|lt=Iwaki City|Q274384|qid=Q274384|1=Iwaki, Fukushima}}, {{ill|lt=Fukushima Prefecture|Q71707|qid=Q71707|1=Fukushima Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha (minor shrine)|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and under the {{ill|lt=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was designated a prefectural shrine.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it was founded in the first year of {{ill|lt=Daido (Japan)|Q1373191|qid=Q1373191|lt=Daidō|1=Daidō}} ({{ill|lt=806|Q30021|qid=Q30021|1=806}}). It is an {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki-listed shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} and one of the seven Shikinaisha of Iwaki Province. In ancient times it was said to be the general guardian shrine of the four districts of Iwaki ({{ill|lt=Kikuta District|Q11619613|qid=Q11619613|1=Kikuta district}}, {{ill|lt=Iwaki District|Q11587876|qid=Q11587876|1=Iwaki district}}, {{ill|lt=Iwamae District|Q11587858|qid=Q11587858|1=Iwasaki district}}, and {{ill|lt=Naraha District|Q11541347|qid=Q11541347|1=Naraha district}}).

As one of the “Three Shrines of Taira Castle,” deities protecting {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Taira Castle|1=UNKNOWN}}, it was venerated by successive lords of the castle.

In {{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1602|Q6727|qid=Q6727|1=1602}}), construction of {{ill|lt=Iwaki-Taira Castle|Q11587869|qid=Q11587869|1=Iwakitaira Castle}} reduced the shrine’s land, leading to its decline. However, in {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|qid=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}} 9 ({{ill|lt=1826|Q7004|qid=Q7004|1=1826}}), the fourth lord of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Taira Domain|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|lt=Naitō Yoshitsuna|Q8514975|qid=Q8514975|1=Naitō Yoshimune}}, restored a small {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Inari|1=UNKNOWN}} shrine that had stood in Sakuramachi and relocated it to the present site.

In March of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was elevated to the rank of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}. Even after the abolition of the {{ill|lt=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 21, it continued to be affectionately called “Kensha” (prefectural shrine).

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 7, the {{ill|lt=cliff|Q1174791|qid=Q1174791|1=Escarpment}} on the southern front was cut away to create the “Men’s Slope,” and in {{ill|lt=Taishō|Q329174|qid=Q329174|1=Taishō era}} 10 the “Women’s Slope” was completed.

=== Shrine Name ===
“{{ill|lt=Ko|Q1307938|qid=Q1307938|1=Ko}}” is said to mean “{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=silkworm|1=UNKNOWN}},” symbolizing “clothing”; the agricultural tool “{{ill|lt=hoe|Q131154|qid=Q131154|1=Hoe (tool)}}” represents “food”; and “{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kura (storehouse)|1=UNKNOWN}}” represents “shelter.” Together, the name is said to express the divine virtues of the enshrined deity governing “{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=clothing, food, and shelter|1=UNKNOWN}}.”

=== Shrine Buildings ===
In April of {{ill|lt=Tenpō|Q1369045|qid=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}} 2, a fire destroyed the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shrine buildings|1=UNKNOWN}}, and most {{ill|lt=ancient documents|Q89298567|qid=Q89298567|1=komonjo}} and {{ill|lt=sacred treasures|Q11589458|qid=Q11589458|1=shinpō}} were lost.

In May of {{ill|lt=Kaei|Q1146125|qid=Q1146125|1=Kaei}} 6, the current main hall was constructed by master carpenter Yokota Mokusaemon of {{ill|lt=Takine Town|Q7678319|qid=Q7678319|1=Takine, Fukushima}}.

Under the design and supervision of Tsukamoto Yoshitaka, a consultant to the {{ill|lt=Ministry of Education (Japan)|Q11080185|qid=Q11080185|1=Ministry of Education, Science, Sports and Culture}}, the present {{ill|lt=Heiden|Q3076699|qid=Q3076699|1=Heiden (Shinto)}} and {{ill|lt=Haiden|Q3125745|qid=Q3125745|1=Haiden (Shinto)}} were completed in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 4.

